    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-07-27T06:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-07-27T06:00:00-05:00" n="231"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d231">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 763.72119/1825</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Vice Consul at Zurich</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">McNally</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d231fn1">Via the Legation in Switzerland, No. 4100, July 27,
                        noon.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Zürich</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date ana="#date_undated-inferred-from-document-content"
                            calendar="gregorian" when="1918-07-27T12:00:00+01:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">undated</hi>
                        </date>. <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received July 29, 1918, 6.14
                        a.m.</hi>]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>My son-in-law has been transferred to the Admiralty in Berlin and there the
                    German Chancellor <persName corresp="#p_HCGFv1">Hertling</persName> requested
                    him to ask me to transmit the President of the United States through the
                    Department of State an acceptance of his peace conditions saying that in no
                    other way could he get the true statement before him. I replied that I was not
                    permitted to without the consent of the Department of State and there the matter
                    has rested for several days. Believing now, however, that my Government would
                    profit by a knowledge of its nature, I am transmitting unknown to them the
                    complete text: <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>German Chancellor fully agrees to the four conditions in President
                                <persName corresp="#p_WW1">Wilson</persName>’s speech at Mount
                            Vernon on the Fourth of July, 1918, and he too considers them as a good
                            basis for peace negotiations. He agrees to these four conditions in the
                            belief that the first generally is not intended to apply to any one
                            stated government but is directed against all autocracies generally.</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">McNally</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
